e progressive Subjection of Women. This volume, by including the often ignored Of Kings’ Treasuries, offers readers full access to Ruskin’s complex and sometimes contradictory views on men and women. The accompanying essays place Sesame and Lilies within historical debates on men, women, culture, and the family. Elizabeth Helsinger examines the text as a meditation on the pleasures of reading, Seth Koven gives a wide-ranging account of how Victorians read Sesame and Lilies, and Jan Marsh situates the work within controversies over educational reform.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBooks and readingzGreat Britain. 0aConduct of life. 0aFemininity. 0aMasculinity. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Essays.2bisacsh1 aHelsinger, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoven, Seth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarsh, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNord, Deborah Epstein, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNord, Deborah Epstein, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRuskin, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030009259240uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030012930440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300129304423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300129304/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY